01:04:56,680 --> 01:05:02,680
and systems are leaner now and they can 
be worked on by fewer numbers of people.

750
01:05:02,680 --> 01:05:04,720
That's an amazing point. I 
remember Elon's being like,  

751
01:05:04,720 --> 01:05:07,200
"Here, we have to throw away the whole 
thing. We have to re-architect everything.  

752
01:05:07,200 --> 01:05:10,160
It's stupid the way it's built." And 
it sounds like that actually worked.

753
01:05:10,160 --> 01:05:10,880
Yeah, so-

754
01:05:10,880 --> 01:05:11,440
Well.

755
01:05:11,440 --> 01:05:14,840
You don't have to rewrite everything 
from scratch. Some things are good,  

756
01:05:14,840 --> 01:05:18,360
I guess, to rewrite. But just 
even deleting the unnecessary  

757
01:05:18,360 --> 01:05:23,160
cruft and keeping the rest of 
the core system, that's awesome.

758
01:05:23,160 --> 01:05:27,200
I love that we're creating a formula to run 
these sorts of companies and teams. There's  

759
01:05:27,200 --> 01:05:33,280
so much here. I want to go back to the building of 
the original product. I took us on a long tangent  

760
01:05:33,280 --> 01:05:39,680
and an amazing tangent, but I heard a story 
of when you launched Birdwatch at that point.  

761
01:05:39,680 --> 01:05:44,480
You specifically wanted to keep expectations 
very low and there was a GIF in the thing,  

762
01:05:44,480 --> 01:05:49,200
and it just looked like clearly this is not ready 
for prime time. Talk about just how you did that,  

763
01:05:49,200 --> 01:05:53,600
how you launched it in a way where people 
weren't like, "It's never going to work."

764
01:05:53,600 --> 01:05:58,880
We were very disciplined, I guess you could 
say, about having the product prove itself  

765
01:05:58,880 --> 01:06:08,120
at every given point. When we built the first 
mockups, these were just pictures of depicting  

766
01:06:08,120 --> 01:06:11,600
what community notes might look like. We showed 
those to people across the political spectrum.  

767
01:06:11,600 --> 01:06:15,840
We saw, hey, people really like these. 
Whether they're on the right or left,  

768
01:06:15,840 --> 01:06:20,360
they seem very open to reading these community 
notes even when they're critical to people of  

769
01:06:20,360 --> 01:06:24,440
their own side. So we're like, "All right. That 
gives us confidence that if we can build this,  

770
01:06:24,440 --> 01:06:28,680
if we can actually make this as a reality, it's 
going to work." Then there's a question of can we  

771
01:06:28,680 --> 01:06:35,680
make it a reality? Will people in the real world 
be able to write notes that are of this quality? 

772
01:06:35,680 --> 01:06:44,000
And so we had an internal pilot test version of 
this where you could write notes. And we first  

773
01:06:44,000 --> 01:06:50,720
basically ran this through an Amazon MTurk type 
of participant test just to see if you just put  

774
01:06:50,720 --> 01:06:57,920
some normal people in there, will they be able to 
write these notes? All those notes weren't good,  

775
01:06:57,920 --> 01:07:02,520
but it was clear that there were people out there 
who could write good notes. So then like, "Okay,  

776
01:07:02,520 --> 01:07:07,320
this is possible. What will happen if we 
actually do this out in the real world?  

777
01:07:07,320 --> 01:07:13,240
And let's run a pilot and find out." And 
so we took that pilot that we'd run the  

778
01:07:13,240 --> 01:07:21,600
MTurk of test on, and we released it to at 
first 1000 people, totally out in public,  

779
01:07:21,600 --> 01:07:27,400
and we didn't know what was going to show up. You 
could imagine the notes could have been terrible. 

780
01:07:27,400 --> 01:07:31,880
And so we were talking, "Well, what do we do? 
We're going to put this out there. Everyone's  

781
01:07:31,880 --> 01:07:35,800
going to have all these questions. They're 
probably going to be really skeptical, and  

782
01:07:35,800 --> 01:07:41,600
we know it might be a total dumpster fire. And so 
what do we do to set expectations appropriately?"  

783
01:07:41,600 --> 01:07:44,080
We felt like we could probably get there in the 
end, but we just didn't know what was going to  

784
01:07:44,080 --> 01:07:48,280
happen at first. We wanted to set expectations, 
and so we're like, "Well, why don't we just  

785
01:07:48,280 --> 01:07:51,680
stick..." There's the page where you see a post 
in the notes below. We're like, "Why don't we  

786
01:07:51,680 --> 01:08:00,360
just stick a dumpster fire GIF on that page?" And 
you go there, you're like, "Hey, anything you see  

787
01:08:00,360 --> 01:08:06,040
below here might just be a total dumpster fire. 
At least it would show we were aware of that as a  

788
01:08:06,040 --> 01:08:13,080
possible risk." In the end, we did not do that. 
It cracked me up, but we thought it was like-

789
01:08:13,080 --> 01:08:16,000
Oh, you didn't actually launch. 
Okay. That was just a concept. Okay.

790
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:20,440
We had mockups of it, and every time 
I looked at the mockup, I laughed,  

791
01:08:20,440 --> 01:08:25,760
but ultimately we had so much to explain on that 
page, like, what is this thing and how does it  

792
01:08:25,760 --> 01:08:29,240
work? Ultimately, we're like, "Okay, this is 
probably going to distract from the point."  

793
01:08:29,960 --> 01:08:35,240
So we pulled it. I wish maybe it had seen the 
light of day at one point, but yeah, ultimately  

794
01:08:35,240 --> 01:08:39,320
we kept it simple and we focused that page on 
explaining what was going on here. But again,  

795
01:08:40,960 --> 01:08:48,000
as has happened many times with the project, we 
put the pilot out there and the notes were good. 

796
01:08:48,000 --> 01:08:51,840
They weren't all good. It was a mixed 
bag, but there was gold in there. And  

797
01:08:51,840 --> 01:08:55,440
from the very early days with just 
1000 contributors, it was obvious  

798
01:08:56,600 --> 01:09:01,480
that people could write notes that were 
informative, that were neutral, that spoke  

799
01:09:01,480 --> 01:09:08,440
to controversial challenging topics, and that 
if we could just identify those from the rest,  

800
01:09:08,440 --> 01:09:12,040
this was going to work. It was going to 
work as well as the very first mockups we  

801
01:09:12,040 --> 01:09:17,840
had made. So that became the focus that is, 
how do we sift out the gold from the rest?

802
01:09:19,520 --> 01:09:23,600
I think you may have shared with this with me, 
when someone noticed you guys were testing this  

803
01:09:23,600 --> 01:09:27,600
and they took screenshots and tweeted it, 
and I think Elon replied, "This is cool."

804
01:09:27,600 --> 01:09:32,640
Yeah. Yeah. So in the very early days 
when it was just a Figma prototype,  

805
01:09:32,640 --> 01:09:38,080
we were running these usertesting.com on moderated 
studies. I guess one of the participants sent  

806
01:09:38,080 --> 01:09:43,480
one to an NBC reporter who wrote a bunch of 
stories on it. Anyway, that day, there was  

807
01:09:43,480 --> 01:09:51,880
a lot of chatter about it on the service, and 
Elon... To put this back in time perspective,  

808
01:09:51,880 --> 01:09:59,680
this is, I think, 2020, so two years before any 
acquisition stuff happened, Elon is just a Twitter  

809
01:09:59,680 --> 01:10:06,720
user building rockets and electric cars and other 
cool stuff and stumbles on this thing that depicts  

810
01:10:06,720 --> 01:10:12,880
the prototype that we've been testing. And he 
writes back, "Definitely worth trying, IMO."  

811
01:10:12,880 --> 01:10:19,560
And I remember thinking that was cool back then 
and it's interesting to see, he's obviously had a  

812
01:10:19,560 --> 01:10:24,760
very consistent point on it. I think the idea was 
appealing and he has obviously been a big fan of  

813
01:10:24,760 --> 01:10:30,960
it in the product and had been a big supporter 
proponent. So yeah, it was cool that it came  

814
01:10:30,960 --> 01:10:36,600
from... that support has been from the very early 
days before he was ever involved in the company.

815
01:10:36,600 --> 01:10:38,840
I love that moment. That must have felt really  

816
01:10:38,840 --> 01:10:42,720
wild for Elon to be commenting on 
this Figma prototype retesting.

817
01:10:42,720 --> 01:10:44,680
It was cool. It was cool.

818
01:10:44,680 --> 01:10:51,440
Oh, man. So when we were preparing for this 
interview, I asked you guys what's the main  

819
01:10:51,440 --> 01:10:55,800
thing you want to make sure people get and 
understand about why community notes has been  

820
01:10:55,800 --> 01:11:02,200
so effective? And Keith, you specifically said 
that it was the principles behind how you wanted  

821
01:11:02,200 --> 01:11:07,040
to approach this and how you continue to stick 
to this throughout. And we'll talk about how  

822
01:11:07,040 --> 01:11:11,680
you kept it alive throughout all these different 
CO changes in leaders. But just talk about these  

823
01:11:11,680 --> 01:11:16,760
principles, what the actual principles are 
and why that was so key to it working out.

824
01:11:16,760 --> 01:11:22,200
There are a number of principles that I think 
when we first shared them with people at the  

825
01:11:22,200 --> 01:11:28,160
company seemed maybe a little bit crazy. But 
I think they are the reason the product works,  

826
01:11:28,160 --> 01:11:33,480
and I think they've been very important, and we 
do. We come back to them regularly, today, all  

827
01:11:33,480 --> 01:11:41,000
the time. Probably the craziest one is just that 
this thing is going to be the voice of the people.  

828
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:46,240
It's going to represent the voice of people. It's 
not going to represent the company's voice. So it  

829
01:11:46,240 --> 01:11:51,640
is not a tech company deciding what shows. It 
is the people deciding what shows, and that  

830
01:11:51,640 --> 01:11:58,880
had a lot of implications on the design. First of 
all, we don't have a button that will change the  

831
01:11:58,880 --> 01:12:05,760
status of a note. So if a note is showing because 
the people have rated it and found it helpful,  

832
01:12:05,760 --> 01:12:10,800
it is going to show. We can't change that.
And that is the kind of thing that when we first  

833
01:12:10,800 --> 01:12:16,800
propose this, that's unsettling to people. They're 
like, "Wait, so something can go up and the  

834
01:12:16,800 --> 01:12:21,960
company can't take it down, or can't change its 
status, get it to stop showing." And we're like,  

835
01:12:21,960 --> 01:12:26,760
"Yeah, and it has to work that well. If it doesn't 
work well enough to do that, then it doesn't  

836
01:12:26,760 --> 01:12:32,240
work." This is one of our key principles was, 
if there's a problem with a note that's so bad,  

837
01:12:32,240 --> 01:12:37,000
you want to do something about it's a problem 
with the system. We need to redesign the system  

838
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:43,800
to be showing good notes. And so yeah, we had 
to get everyone comfortable with the idea that  

839
01:12:43,800 --> 01:12:50,280
there was no button to change the status of a 
note. Similarly, as we talked about earlier,  

840
01:12:50,280 --> 01:12:55,120
we wanted this to represent all of humanity.
And so we didn't want to be arbiters of who  

841
01:12:56,120 --> 01:13:01,600
can come in and be a contributor and who can't. 
So we open it to everyone. You just have to meet a  

842
01:13:01,600 --> 01:13:05,840
really basic objective criteria. You have to have 
a verified phone to help reduce the likelihood of  

843
01:13:05,840 --> 01:13:12,160
having bots or things like that participating. 
But beyond that, it's random selection and it  

844
01:13:12,160 --> 01:13:17,680
still is that way today. And again, that people 
took some time to get people comfortable with  

845
01:13:17,680 --> 01:13:25,120
it. But I think that the fact that this is the 
voice of the people and reflects their output  

846
01:13:25,640 --> 01:13:31,560
through an open and transparent process is 
so key to both why it is good, why it works,  

847
01:13:31,560 --> 01:13:38,360
but also why it's trusted. So that's 
number one and I think will forever be  

848
01:13:38,360 --> 01:13:46,760
the heart of the product. Another one that 
people thought was crazy was transparency. 

849
01:13:49,200 --> 01:13:54,840
The previous approaches to dealing with 
misleading info, it felt to a lot of people,  

850
01:13:54,840 --> 01:14:02,440
like black box tech companies or media companies 
or leads or whatever making decisions. We're like,  

851
01:14:02,440 --> 01:14:05,880
"People need to get comfortable with this. They 
need to trust this. So the whole thing has to be  

852
01:14:05,880 --> 01:14:11,920
out in the open." The code that decides what notes 
share has to be out in the open. All of the data  

853
01:14:11,920 --> 01:14:17,200
and ratings that make it happen have to be out 
in the open. People should be able to take the  

854
01:14:17,200 --> 01:14:22,440
code and data and replicate the whole service 
and that we have done exactly what we've said  

855
01:14:22,440 --> 01:14:26,480
we've done. And they should be able to audit 
it. They should be able to go and look and say,  

856
01:14:26,480 --> 01:14:30,520
"Hey, I think this part could be better."
Or if they think we're biased, they should be able  

857
01:14:30,520 --> 01:14:35,920
to work with the data and point it out. And if 
people have good observations, that should factor  

858
01:14:35,920 --> 01:14:42,000
back into the code. And this is, again, something 
that's difficult to get people comfortable with,  

859
01:14:42,000 --> 01:14:45,800
that everything is out there, you can't cover 
anything up. But I think that's so essential to  

860
01:14:45,800 --> 01:14:55,000
people trusting it. Yeah, we set these out on day 
one. We go back to them constantly because we're  

861
01:14:56,360 --> 01:15:00,840
always evolving the product, and we're always 
like got to make sure every new change is open.  

862
01:15:00,840 --> 01:15:06,040
Whenever we update the scoring system, there's an 
update in GitHub when the data is published daily  

863
01:15:06,040 --> 01:15:11,800
so you can download it. And so yeah, I think those 
have been really essential to the thing working.

864
01:15:12,400 --> 01:15:19,040
And by the way, these do not come without a 
cost. It's actually really hard from an end  

865
01:15:19,040 --> 01:15:24,440
perspective to actually open source the actual 
algorithm that's running on the actual data.  

866
01:15:25,200 --> 01:15:28,960
Because the way large-scale services 
like this are usually architected does  

867
01:15:28,960 --> 01:15:36,880
not naturally lend itself to being run as a 
script by someone who's downloaded a TSV. So  

868
01:15:36,880 --> 01:15:42,080
we actually have to take weird architectural 
decisions to make this possible in a way that  

869
01:15:42,080 --> 01:15:45,200
probably wouldn't have been if we didn't 
start with this assumption from scratch.  

870
01:15:45,200 --> 01:15:49,120
We would've had to maybe rewrite 
the system to make it like this.

871
01:15:49,120 --> 01:15:50,440
What's an example of that?

872
01:15:50,440 --> 01:15:55,400
For instance, there's a matrix 
factorization that we train. Usually, you  

873
01:15:55,400 --> 01:16:03,640
would train a matrix factor... train your 
ML model once and then serve it, I guess  

874
01:16:03,640 --> 01:16:11,120
with a separate service. But we didn't want to 
have people externally spinning up services to  

875
01:16:11,120 --> 01:16:18,360
be able to replicate the system that we had. 
So basically, I don't think it would've been  

876
01:16:18,360 --> 01:16:24,920
actually very cool if we had open sourced the code 
in a way that wasn't actually runnable, I guess,  

877
01:16:26,840 --> 01:16:31,760
by someone just... At this point, you 
can download Python code and run a  

878
01:16:31,760 --> 01:16:35,800
script. You do need a lot of RAM right 
now, but you can do it on one machine.

879
01:16:35,800 --> 01:16:37,720
Okay. How much RAM are we talking about?

880
01:16:37,720 --> 01:16:39,868
Oh, only like 500 gigs.

881
01:16:39,868 --> 01:16:40,280
Okay. Okay. That's reasonable.

882
01:16:40,280 --> 01:16:45,640
It'll take a day if you don't do anything 
special to speed it up. Good to know, but yeah.

883
01:16:45,640 --> 01:16:46,040
Cool.

884
01:16:46,040 --> 01:16:51,000
Possible is the key thing, and people have 
done it. Vitalik Buterin had a blog post  

885
01:16:51,000 --> 01:16:57,280
where he talks about his explorations, making 
sure the algorithm really does what it says  

886
01:16:57,280 --> 01:17:05,400
it does. And I think just the fact that a 
handful of people have done this, there's  

887
01:17:05,400 --> 01:17:11,720
enough people who have done it that there's 
someone you'd probably trust who's verified it.

888
01:17:11,720 --> 01:17:16,640
And that's rolling out to Meta. No big deal. 
I love just as you described these principles,  

889
01:17:16,640 --> 01:17:21,680
just I could imagine a PM at a company being like, 
"Okay, guys. Here, I want to do this project."  

890
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:27,520
There's so much idealism to it that rarely works 
in real life; going to be open source. You're  

891
01:17:27,520 --> 01:17:31,080
going to give it to everyone. We don't have actual 
control over what it's going to do, don't worry  

892
01:17:31,080 --> 01:17:36,840
about it. It's going to just change the way people 
see this thing that we've been very careful about  

893
01:17:36,840 --> 01:17:42,320
and then it works. And I think that's very rare 
and it's really impressive. And what I'm hearing  

894
01:17:42,320 --> 01:17:47,880
partly is that sticking to those principles was 
actually really fundamental to it working and not  

895
01:17:49,640 --> 01:17:53,720
bending over when someone's like, "No, no, no, 
we can't do this. What if we change this part?"

896
01:17:53,720 --> 01:17:59,080
I think if we had broken with any of those 
principles, if there was anything black box,  

897
01:17:59,080 --> 01:18:04,440
if there was whatever, the product would 
be a lot harder to trust. And so I think  

898
01:18:04,440 --> 01:18:10,920
it's because we've just stuck to them so 
cleanly simply that people can trust it.

899
01:18:10,920 --> 01:18:15,560
You've talked about a few moments when it 
was like, wow, the White House changed their  

900
01:18:15,560 --> 01:18:20,200
announcement because of the community note. We 
talked about the dog is a cat. Are there any other  

901
01:18:20,200 --> 01:18:26,120
moments that after you launched of, "Holy shit, 
this is working? This is going to actually work."

902
01:18:26,120 --> 01:18:34,920
All along, we saw it working. We wanted to 
be confident whenever we expanded it to new  

903
01:18:34,920 --> 01:18:38,280
audiences or new countries or whatever, we 
wanted to be confident it was going to work.  

904
01:18:38,280 --> 01:18:44,600
So maybe held our breath a little bit just 
to see that it would do what we expected,  

905
01:18:44,600 --> 01:18:48,040
but we always expected that. But 
that said, there were definitely  

906
01:18:48,040 --> 01:18:54,720
stress cases. The one that comes to mind 
is the start of the Israel Hamas conflict  

907
01:18:55,840 --> 01:19:04,920
in 2023 in October. That was probably the largest 
deluge of misleading information I've ever seen  

908
01:19:04,920 --> 01:19:11,560
shared on the internet at one time. It was 
overwhelming. A number of photos and videos  

909
01:19:11,560 --> 01:19:19,280
and whatever coming out related to that, it 
was insane. And just to give you an example,  

910
01:19:19,840 --> 01:19:27,440
I think it was first three days or something 
of that conflict, we had 500 notes covering  

911
01:19:27,440 --> 01:19:35,400
all sorts of different... out of context imagery.
Someone would say, "Hey, this is happening here."  

912
01:19:35,400 --> 01:19:41,440
It's actually from 2013 in Syria. There 
were people making fake battle footage  

913
01:19:41,440 --> 01:19:45,320
in the video game simulator Arma 
3. So there were notes explaining,  

914
01:19:45,320 --> 01:19:51,200
this stuff looked realistic. And unless you saw 
the note, you wouldn't really know. There are all  

915
01:19:51,200 --> 01:19:57,280
sorts of claims about what was going on in the 
ground, and that was definitely... The product  

916
01:19:57,280 --> 01:20:02,680
was still pretty new at that point. We'd expanded 
in the U. S. less than a year before that. We had  

917
01:20:02,680 --> 01:20:09,880
been rolling out throughout the world that year 
and then this large event happened. And I felt  

918
01:20:09,880 --> 01:20:16,240
like we were just enough prepared at the right 
time for the system to be able to handle that. 

919
01:20:16,240 --> 01:20:20,600
Probably one of the most important things we did 
right before that was launch the ability to write  

920
01:20:20,600 --> 01:20:28,560
notes on images and videos and have those matched 
to other posts. I remember at that time thinking,  

921
01:20:29,440 --> 01:20:35,760
"Wow, I'm glad we launched that feature a few 
months ago versus still had it on the shelf,"  

922
01:20:35,760 --> 01:20:41,880
because it was really important in that conflict. 
And I think even it was just a few weeks before we  

923
01:20:41,880 --> 01:20:47,960
had launched a major speed up in notes too. When 
we first built the product, the number one focus  

924
01:20:47,960 --> 01:20:54,280
was always quality. We knew that the product 
would live and die by the quality of the notes.  

925
01:20:54,280 --> 01:20:57,920
That was the thing we could never give up on. We 
also knew it needed to deliver speed and scale,  

926
01:20:57,920 --> 01:21:00,400
but we're like, "We will get the quality in the 
right place, and we can speed it up and scale-

927
01:21:00,400 --> 01:21:05,240
Get the quality in the right place and we can 
speed it up and scale it out over time. And we  

928
01:21:05,240 --> 01:21:12,040
had actually just launched a speed-up that took 
three hours off the time it needed to go live,  

929
01:21:12,040 --> 01:21:16,080
and it was I think a matter of weeks 
before that conflict happened, so again,  

930
01:21:16,080 --> 01:21:20,640
super glad that was out there. In the first 
few days of the conflict the median time  

931
01:21:20,640 --> 01:21:24,560
from a post going live to a note showing up 
was five hours, which is like crazy fast.  

932
01:21:25,640 --> 01:21:28,760
Typical fact checking is like two to 
four, at least it's really common to  

933
01:21:28,760 --> 01:21:33,600
see it take two to four days. These notes 
were showing up in five hours and we're like,  

934
01:21:33,600 --> 01:21:40,200
we are so glad we got those things out before this 
happened, it made the service a lot more helpful.

935
01:21:40,200 --> 01:21:49,400
One other thing that was, I think, nice to see 
working then was, one criticism of Community  

936
01:21:49,400 --> 01:21:54,800
Notes some people bring up is, well if you always 
need agreement from people who typically disagree,  

937
01:21:54,800 --> 01:22:00,640
then in these super polarized settings, 
that conflict being probably number one,  

938
01:22:00,640 --> 01:22:07,200
then you wouldn't see any notes. But actually 
the reality was there were tons of notes about  

939
01:22:07,200 --> 01:22:15,320
that conflict. So I think there was this 
kind of nice property where actually,  

940
01:22:15,320 --> 01:22:18,720
and maybe this is a surprising fact, that 
there's more agreement out there across  

941
01:22:18,720 --> 01:22:24,520
polarized divides than maybe conventional wisdom 
says, and the places where people agreed were  

942
01:22:25,080 --> 01:22:30,440
really objectively true and verifiable. I guess 
maybe this is more true the more polarized the  

943
01:22:30,440 --> 01:22:38,760
setting is, but where the agreement actually 
lends you, and basically notes that are very  

944
01:22:38,760 --> 01:22:44,960
neutrally written, very focused on the 
facts and easy to verify information.

945
01:22:45,920 --> 01:22:52,440
There's this talk for a while of just there's 
no more facts, nobody believes there is a single  

946
01:22:52,440 --> 01:22:59,120
true fact anymore, everything is subjective, and 
I think Community Notes proves the opposite. Facts  

947
01:22:59,120 --> 01:23:03,720
matter, there are facts that we can all agree 
with even on the most controversial topics.

948
01:23:03,720 --> 01:23:11,040
Yeah, we saw this really from day one, when 
we would show those prototypes to people just  

949
01:23:11,040 --> 01:23:16,920
depicting the idea, it was really obvious that 
