980
01:26:13,440 --> 01:26:17,520
Okay, just a few more questions. There 
was an audience question asked on Twitter,  

981
01:26:17,520 --> 01:26:20,480
we all asked on Twitter, "What do people 
want to know about Community Notes?" one  

982
01:26:20,480 --> 01:26:26,680
was actually why you guys switched to anonymous 
contributors, what was the decision behind that?

983
01:26:26,680 --> 01:26:32,640
Yeah, we had this pilot where we were 
testing with a small number of contributors,  

984
01:26:32,640 --> 01:26:36,520
a few thousand contributors, and we learned a 
lot through that pilot. Probably the biggest  

985
01:26:36,520 --> 01:26:43,120
thing we learned was related to anonymity 
or pseudonymity of contributors. We had  

986
01:26:43,120 --> 01:26:48,000
originally assumed that it was important that 
people contribute under their real handle,  

987
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:52,240
or their real name, or whatever it was. 
The first prototypes depicted that,  

988
01:26:52,240 --> 01:26:56,120
we kind of thought that would be important 
for people trusting the note, and actually  

989
01:26:56,120 --> 01:27:02,520
it was totally wrong. The best option was 
actually opposite of what we first tried. 

990
01:27:02,520 --> 01:27:09,880
We found a few things. One, people were hesitant 
to write a note on a controversial topic because  

991
01:27:09,880 --> 01:27:15,280
they didn't want to get attacked or harassed 
online. And so some people were comfortable  

992
01:27:15,280 --> 01:27:18,960
doing this but others were not, and so it 
meant there was more potential good notes  

993
01:27:18,960 --> 01:27:24,520
to be written than were getting written, and 
this was very clear feedback from the pilot. 

994
01:27:24,520 --> 01:27:31,600
Two, and this is super interesting, people are 
actually more willing to cross partisan boundaries  

995
01:27:31,600 --> 01:27:36,360
when they are anonymous or pseudonymous 
than when they are under their real name,  

996
01:27:36,360 --> 01:27:42,320
and it intuitively makes a lot of sense. If 
you publicly are using your name, you feel  

997
01:27:42,320 --> 01:27:48,560
are affiliated with one side versus the other, 
you might hesitate to be perceived as breaking  

998
01:27:48,560 --> 01:27:55,120
with that side. But you may actually, for example, 
find a note helpful that's critical of that side,  

999
01:27:55,120 --> 01:27:59,200
and there's a bunch of studies that show when 
people are anonymous, they're much more willing  

1000
01:27:59,200 --> 01:28:02,280
to cross partisan boundaries and work with 
the other side, agree with the other side,  

1001
01:28:02,280 --> 01:28:07,760
and we saw that too. And so by allowing people 
to be pseudonymous, you actually get more honest  

1002
01:28:07,760 --> 01:28:10,820
answers about what they really think and 
it helps find disagreement that really-

1003
01:28:10,820 --> 01:28:12,400
That's so counterintuitive.

1004
01:28:12,400 --> 01:28:12,600
Yes.

1005
01:28:12,600 --> 01:28:16,480
You never hear the opposite always, and 
it's so interesting it's the opposite.

1006
01:28:16,480 --> 01:28:17,080
Yeah, yeah.

1007
01:28:17,080 --> 01:28:21,360
I think the same principle applies 
to making the likes private.

1008
01:28:21,360 --> 01:28:22,560
I was just thinking that.

1009
01:28:22,560 --> 01:28:22,960
Yeah.

1010
01:28:22,960 --> 01:28:27,480
Yeah, I like a lot more stuff that's a little, 
definitely, I wouldn't have liked, yeah.

